         <listPerson>
            <person sex="1">
               <persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth">አበበ፡ አረጋይ፡</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">ʾAbbaba ʾAragāy</persName>
                  <persName>
                  <roleName type="title">rās</roleName>
               </persName>
                  <nationality type="Ethiopia"/>
                  <faith type="EOTC"/>
                  
                  
               <occupation type="military">patriot</occupation>
                  
                  <birth when="1903"/>
                  
                  
                  
               <floruit notBefore="1930" notAfter="1960">He was one of the outstanding Ethiopian patriots during the Italian occupation, <date>1935-1941</date>. 
                  He was a native of <placeName ref="LOC3433Jerru"/> in <placeName ref="LOC6574NorthSawa"/>. ʾAbbaba ʾAragāy 
                  joined the city guards of <placeName ref="LOC1216AddisA"/> when they were established in <date>1930</date>. Following the Italians triumphant entry into the capital,<date>1936</date>, 
                  he organized a center of  armed resistance in his native district and soon emerged as the leader of patriotic forces in <placeName ref="LOC6574NorthSawa"/>.
                  He participated in the ill coordinated offensive of July <date>1936</date>. He was promoted to the rank of <roleName type="title">rās</roleName>by 
                  <persName ref="PRS6575Malaka"/> who had been elected <roleName type="title">nǝguś</roleName> by the patriots of <placeName ref="LOC2008Bulga"/>. 
                  He was also made honorary chairman of the Association of the patriots of Old Ethiopia, created for the purpose of fostering unity among the disperate patriotic groups. 
                  He welcomed the triumphant entry of <persName ref="PRS5226haylase"/> at the head of 15,000 troops in <date>1941</date>. 
                  He was soon appointed as mayor of <placeName ref="LOC1216AddisA"/>. He served also the Imperial government as Minister of Defence and Minister of Interior.
                   </floruit>
               <death when="1960">He was one of the ministers and dignitaries killed in the course of the abortive Coup d'état in <date>1960</date>.</death>
                  
                  
